    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-26T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-26T20:00:00-05:00" n="903"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d903">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/11–1345: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-26T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 26, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>211. 1. Negotiations proceeding slowly on basis Crowley’s discussion of 560
                    million dollars ExImBank credit with Soong. Rumor reported Urtel 206, November
                    13, 11 A.M. untrue and little progress in negotiations since Deptel 1705,
                    October 19, 6 P.M. to Chungking.</p>
                <p>2. Department now preparing statement on desired undertakings in nature of <hi
                        rend="italic">quid pro quo.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>3. Article IX of draft commercial treaty heretofore submitted covers these
                    points. Article VII of Treaty Relinquishing Extraterritoriality<note n="80"
                        xml:id="d903fn80">Signed at Washington, January 11, 1943, Department of
                        State Treaty Series No. 984, or 57 Stat. 767.</note> provided for early
                    conclusion of commercial treaty and <pb facs="1196" n="1186" xml:id="pg_1186"/>
                    Department probably will urge prompt negotiation as part of undertakings to be
                    requested. Statement in Urtel 206 re machine tool exports immediate prewar years
                    not supported by facts known here. Please send details by airgram.</p>
                <p>4. For your confidential information, trade agreement proposals are being
                    formulated and will be brought to China’s attention in due course.</p>
                <p>5. Interested divisions and Departments are considering these questions but from
                    point of view of interests of both countries. It is believed that some
                    restriction of imports may prove unavoidable for a time but safeguards should be
                    sought against discrimination.</p>
                <p>6. Department believes situation requires consideration of China’s total balance
                    of payments with all countries not merely with United States.</p>
                <p>7. Department’s attitude is that credits must be considered primarily in relation
                    to China’s needed rehabilitation and development but interests of this country
                    in trade and investment should be safeguarded.</p>
                <p>Foregoing views are provisional not final.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
